In terms of organized religion they normally fall in to 2 broad categories, those that take their religious books literally, and those that say that they are just metaphors and are open to interpretation....<br>
So the literalists (Orthodox Jews, Pentecostal, Seventh day Adventists, etc) see life as only in existence for an insanely small time; five to six thousand years(not sure what the current Jewish year is) or so for Jews(The Jewish calendar is based upon the garden of Eden, a lot of reformed/conservative Jews don't know that), twelve to thirteen thousand for fundamentalist Christians. In these cases the carbon dating, and dinosaur fossils cause a problem, the normal response of which is that God is a prankster and only put these 'facts' here to fool us.<br>
The metaphoric/liberal interpretations, say that all of the Old/New testament are parables to teach us something and are not to be taken literally. Well then why does the line for interpretation need to stop just before God... Why can't God be thought of as a symbol. Isn't an Agnostic or an Atheist one who just goes the next step and says the teachings/bible are nothing more then a moral road map of society as a whole(although a lot of the 'moral' things would be considered barbaric now a days)?<br>
-----------------------------------------------------<br>
